{
  "doc_id": "9949",
  "text": "In order to dissect biochemical processes of translation unique to higher plant chloroplasts, we have developed an in vitro translation system from tobacco chloroplasts. Our in vitro system supports reproducibly accurate initiation of translation from a variety of chloroplast mRNAs. Hence it provides a powerful tool for the functional analysis of regulatory elements/factors and of the role of low molecular mass compounds [CITATION_1] . Using this in vitro system, we identified three distinct cis-acting elements in the 5 0 -UTR of tobacco psbA mRNA. Among them, RBS1 (AAG) and RBS2 (UGAUGAU) are complementary to the 3 0 terminal region of chloroplast 16S rRNA, and the AU-box (UAAAUAAA, À21 to À14) located between RBS1 and RBS2 is likely to be a binding site of putative trans-acting factor(s). An SD-like sequence (GGAG) located at À36 to À33 is not important for translation. We then assessed the role for translation of SD-like sequences in tobacco chloroplast mRNAs [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The atpE, rps14 and rbcL mRNAs possess SD-like sequences (GGAG at À18 to À15, GGA at À14 to À12 and GGAGG at À10 to À6, respectively) at a position similar to the conserved region observed in Escherichia coli mRNAs, and these sequences were found to be essential for translation. On the other hand, SD-like sequences in the rps12 mRNA and in the petB mRNA are located far from (À44 to À42) and too close to (À5 to À2) the initiation codon, respectively, and these sequences are not essential for translation. Unexpectedly, an SD-like sequence (GGAG) at a proper position (À8 to À5) was not required and even inhibitory for translation of tobacco rps2 mRNA [CITATION_4] . In addition, translation of the tobacco ndhD mRNA starts only from the AUG codon created by RNA editing where no SD-like sequence is present in the 5 0 -UTR, suggesting that translational initiation of ndhD mRNAs depends on a novel sequence element(s) [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
